Thompson

Target IP: 10.10.171.101

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine. The target could be vulnerable to the Ghostcat LFI as it is using 8.x version of Apache.

Enumeration

Port 8080: HTTP


The target machine is running Apache Tomcat 8.5.5 on this port.


Performing a nikto scan against this port shows interesting result. It managed to obtain the default credentials of tomcat:s3cret for the web application. I can spray this against /manager. I managed to successfully login to the web application using the credential found by nikto.


Checking if the target machine is vulnerable to Ghostcat LFI proved true.

Exploitation


I used msfvenom to create a reverse jsp shell and saved it as shell.war.


Then I uploaded the reverse shell. I started a listener on port 80 on my machine for the connection and clicked on the shell above to receive a reverse shell connection on my port 80.


Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as tomcat.

Privilege Escalation



There is an interesting cronjob called id.sh.


I have full privileges over this script file; meaning, I can update it and put my reverse shell here to gain a root shell.


And I received a root shell by exploiting the id.sh. I put the reverse shell script inside this file (as highlighted in yellow on the top picture in the picture above) and I received a root shell on port 21 (as shown on the terminal below on the picture above).

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the target machine as tomcat.


The root.txt flag once I exploited the cronjob to gain a root shell.
